Performing data augmentation:¶

Data augmentation is used to artificially expand the size and variability of the training dataset. This helps improve the robustness and generalization ability of the model. Specifically:

Rescaling: Normalizes the pixel values to the [0, 1] range, which helps in faster convergence and better performance of the neural network. Rotation: Randomly rotates images to make the model invariant to the orientation of the objects. Horizontal Flip: Randomly flips images horizontally to ensure the model learns features independent of their horizontal orientation.

In [5]:
train_dir = './dataset'
In [6]:
train_datagen = ImageDataGenerator(
                rescale=1./255,         # Rescale the pixel values from [0, 255] to [0, 1]
                rotation_range=0.18,    # Randomly rotate images by up to 18 degrees
                validation_split=0.1,
                horizontal_flip=True)   # Randomly flip images horizontally

train_generator = train_datagen.flow_from_directory(
                train_dir,               # Directory of training images
                target_size=(224,224),   # Resize all images to 224x224 pixels
                batch_size=16,
                subset='training',
                class_mode='sparse',      # Mode of labels; 'sparse' means labels are integers (for sparse categorical cross-entropy)
                seed=42)
validation_generator = train_datagen.flow_from_directory(
                train_dir,
                target_size=(224,224),
                batch_size=16,
                subset='validation',
                class_mode='sparse',
                seed=42)

Data Visualization:¶

When you get predictions from your model, they will be in the form of integer labels. Using reverse_classes, you can convert these integer labels back to human-readable class names.

In [7]:
classes = train_generator.class_indices # {'class1': 0, 'class2': 1, 'class3': 2}
reverse_classes = {val: key for key, val in classes.items()} # {0: 'class1', 1: 'class2', 2: 'class3'}
In [8]:
# Initialize set to track collected classes and list to store one image per class
class_collected = set()
img_set = []

# Collect one image for each class
while len(class_collected) < len(reverse_classes):
    images, labels = next(train_generator)  # Fetch next batch of images and labels
    for label, image in zip(labels, images):
        if label not in class_collected:  # Check if the class is already collected
            class_collected.add(label)  # Add label to set
            img_set.append(image)  # Add image to list
        if len(class_collected) == len(reverse_classes):  # Break if all classes are collected
            break

# Convert set of class labels to list
class_collected = list(class_collected)

    ax.set_title(f'Class: {reverse_classes[class_collected[i]]}')

import os
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

# Setup directory paths
base_dir = 'dataset'
glioma_tumor_dir = os.path.join(base_dir, 'glioma_tumor')
meningioma_tumor_dir = os.path.join(base_dir, 'meningioma_tumor')
normal_dir = os.path.join(base_dir, 'normal')
pituitary_tumor_dir = os.path.join(base_dir, 'pituitary_tumor')

# Function to count files in a directory
def get_image_count(image_dir):
    return len([name for name in os.listdir(image_dir) if os.path.isfile(os.path.join(image_dir, name))])

# Get counts for each category
glioma_count = get_image_count(glioma_tumor_dir)
meningioma_count = get_image_count(meningioma_tumor_dir)
normal_count = get_image_count(normal_dir)
pituitary_count = get_image_count(pituitary_tumor_dir)

# Plotting the results
categories = ['Glioma', 'Meningioma', 'Normal', 'Pituitary']
counts = [glioma_count, meningioma_count, normal_count, pituitary_count]
colors = ['#8dd3c7', '#bebada', '#fb8072', '#80b1d3']   # Custom colors for each bar

plt.figure(figsize=(10, 5))
bars = plt.bar(categories, counts, color=colors)

# Add text labels above the bars
for bar, count in zip(bars, counts):
    yval = bar.get_height()
    plt.text(bar.get_x() + bar.get_width()/2, yval, round(count, 1), va='bottom')  # va: vertical alignment

plt.ylabel('Number of Images')
plt.title('Dataset Distribution')
# plt.grid(False, which='major', linewidth='0.5', color='grey')  # Add grid lines
plt.show()

CNN Model:¶

In [17]:
from tensorflow.keras import layers,models
In [18]:
model = models.Sequential()

model.add(keras.layers.Conv2D(input_shape = (224,224,3),kernel_size=(3,3),
                                activation='relu',filters = 32,strides=1))
model.add(keras.layers.MaxPooling2D((2,2)))
model.add(keras.layers.Conv2D(kernel_size=(3,3),activation='relu',filters = 64,
                             strides=1))
model.add(keras.layers.MaxPooling2D((2,2)))
model.add(keras.layers.Conv2D(kernel_size=(3,3),activation='relu',filters = 128,
                             strides=1))
model.add(keras.layers.MaxPooling2D((2,2)))
model.add(keras.layers.Flatten())
model.add(layers.Dropout(0.4))
model.add(keras.layers.Dense(128,activation='relu',
                             kernel_regularizer=keras.regularizers.l2(0.01)))
model.add(keras.layers.Dense(64,activation='relu',
                            kernel_regularizer=keras.regularizers.l2(0.01)))
model.add(keras.layers.Dense(4,activation='softmax'))

Data Poisoning¶

In [10]:
# Define the directory containing the dataset
dataset_dir = './dataset'

# Assuming the dataset is organized such that each class has its own subdirectory
classes = sorted(os.listdir(dataset_dir))

# Initialize lists to store image paths and labels
image_paths = []
labels = []

# Iterate over each class directory
for i, class_name in enumerate(classes):
    class_dir = os.path.join(dataset_dir, class_name)
    # Iterate over each image in the class directory
    for image_name in os.listdir(class_dir):
        image_path = os.path.join(class_dir, image_name)
        image_paths.append(image_path)
        labels.append(i)  # Assign a numerical label to each class

# Convert lists to numpy arrays
image_paths = np.array(image_paths)
labels = np.array(labels)
In [11]:
# Define the flip fraction and target classes
flip_fraction = 0.5  # 50% of the data will be flipped
target_classes = [0, 2]  # Example: Flip labels to all classes

# Function to flip labels
def flip_labels(labels, flip_fraction, target_classes):
    num_labels_to_flip = int(len(labels) * flip_fraction)
    flip_indices = np.random.choice(len(labels), size=num_labels_to_flip, replace=False)

    # Create a copy of labels to avoid modifying the original array
    flipped_labels = labels.copy()
    for index in flip_indices:
        # Randomly select one of the target classes for each flipped label
        new_class = np.random.choice(target_classes)
        flipped_labels[index] = new_class

    return flipped_labels

# Flip the labels
flipped_labels = flip_labels(labels, flip_fraction, target_classes)
In [12]:
import shutil

# Define the directory to save the flipped dataset
flipped_dataset_dir = './flipped_dataset'

# Create directories for each class in the flipped dataset
for class_name in classes:
    class_dir = os.path.join(flipped_dataset_dir, class_name)
    os.makedirs(class_dir, exist_ok=True)

# Copy images to the corresponding class directories with flipped labels
for image_path, label in zip(image_paths, flipped_labels):
    class_name = classes[label]
    dest_dir = os.path.join(flipped_dataset_dir, class_name)
    shutil.copy(image_path, dest_dir)

print("Flipped dataset saved successfully.")

Flipped dataset saved successfully.

import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import cv2

# Define the number of images to display
num_images_to_display = 10

# Create subplots for 2 rows and 5 columns
fig, axes = plt.subplots(2, 5, figsize=(20, 10))

# Set spacing between subplots
plt.subplots_adjust(wspace=0.1, hspace=0.1)

# Iterate over a few randomly selected indices
for idx, i in enumerate(np.random.choice(len(image_paths), num_images_to_display, replace=False)):
    # Load the original image
    original_image = cv2.imread(image_paths[i])
    
    # Calculate the position in the subplot grid
    row = idx // 5
    col = idx % 5
    
    # Display the original image
    axes[row, col].imshow(cv2.cvtColor(original_image, cv2.COLOR_BGR2RGB))
    axes[row, col].axis('off')
    
    # Print the actual and flipped labels
    actual_label = classes[labels[i]]
    flipped_label = classes[flipped_labels[i]]
    axes[row, col].text(0.5, -0.15, f'Actual: {actual_label}\nFlipped: {flipped_label}', fontsize=12, ha='center', transform=axes[row, col].transAxes)

plt.suptitle('Images with Actual and Flipped Labels', fontsize=18)
plt.show()

hist = pd.DataFrame(flipped_model.history)
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

# Creating a figure with a specific size
plt.figure(figsize=(16, 6))

# Plotting training and validation loss
plt.subplot(1, 2, 1)
plt.plot(hist['loss'], label='Train Loss', color='blue', linestyle='--', marker='o', linewidth=2, markersize=6)
plt.plot(hist['val_loss'], label='Validation Loss', color='red', linestyle='-', marker='x', linewidth=2, markersize=6)
plt.title('Train Loss & Validation Loss', fontsize=20)
plt.xlabel('Epochs', fontsize=14)
plt.ylabel('Loss', fontsize=14)
plt.legend(fontsize=12)
plt.grid(True, linestyle='--')

# Plotting training and validation accuracy
plt.subplot(1, 2, 2)
plt.plot(hist['accuracy'], label='Train Accuracy', color='blue', linestyle='--', marker='o', linewidth=2, markersize=6)
plt.plot(hist['val_accuracy'], label='Validation Accuracy', color='red', linestyle='-', marker='x', linewidth=2, markersize=6)
plt.title('Train Accuracy & Validation Accuracy', fontsize=20)
plt.xlabel('Epochs', fontsize=14)
plt.ylabel('Accuracy', fontsize=14)
plt.legend(fontsize=12)
plt.grid(True, linestyle='--')

# Adjusting layout to prevent overlap
plt.tight_layout()

# Display the plots
plt.show()

import numpy as np
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

# Assuming you have the actual labels for comparison
actual_labels = validation_generator.classes

# Convert predictions to class labels
actual_pred_labels = np.argmax(actual_predictions, axis=1)
flipped_pred_labels = np.argmax(flipped_predictions, axis=1)

# Get class labels from the generator
class_labels = list(validation_generator.class_indices.keys())

# Function to plot images with labels and predictions
def plot_images_with_predictions(generator, actual_labels, actual_pred_labels, flipped_pred_labels, class_labels, num_images=10):
    plt.figure(figsize=(20, 10))
    generator_iter = iter(generator)
    for i in range(num_images):
        img, label = next(generator_iter)
        plt.subplot(2, num_images // 2, i + 1)
        plt.imshow(img[0])
        plt.title(f"Actual: {class_labels[actual_labels[i]]}\n Base Model: {class_labels[actual_pred_labels[i]]}\nFlipped Model: {class_labels[flipped_pred_labels[i]]}")
        plt.axis('off')
    plt.tight_layout()
    plt.show()

# Plot the first few images with predictions
plot_images_with_predictions(validation_generator, actual_labels, actual_pred_labels, flipped_pred_labels, class_labels, num_images=10)
